// Given relations:
// Student(StudentID, Name)
// Enrollment(StudentID, CourseID)
// Course(CourseID, CourseName)

// Find students enrolled in all courses
Step1: π_CourseID(Course) → All available courses
Step2: π_StudentID, CourseID(Enrollment) ÷ Step1 → Students enrolled in ALL courses
Step3: π_Name(Student ⋈ Step2) → Names of those students

// R(A, B) and S(B, C) with common attribute B
// Natural Join R ⋈ S can be implemented as:

// Step 1: Cartesian Product
Temp1 ← R × S

// Step 2: Selection on common attribute
Temp2 ← σ_R.B = S.B(Temp1)

// Step 3: Projection removing duplicate B
Result ← π_R.A, R.B, S.C(Temp2)

// Or using Theta Join notation:
// Result ← R ⋈_{R.B = S.B} S

// Employee(EmpID, Name, Salary, ManagerID)
// Need to join Employee with itself to compare salaries

// Step 1: Rename Employee to Manager table
Emp ← Employee
Mgr ← ρ_(EmpID→MgrID, Name→MgrName, Salary→MgrSalary)(Employee)

// Step 2: Join on ManagerID = EmpID
Temp ← σ_Emp.ManagerID = Mgr.MgrID(Emp × Mgr)

// Step 3: Select where employee salary > manager salary
Result ← σ_Emp.Salary > Mgr.MgrSalary(Temp)

// Step 4: Project employee names
Final ← π_Emp.Name(Result)

// R(A, B) and S(B, C)
// Left Outer Join R ⟕ S preserves all tuples from R

// Step 1: Natural Join
NJ ← R ⋈ S

// Step 2: Tuples in R not in NJ
NonMatched ← R - π_R(NJ)

// Step 3: Add NULL for S attributes
NullExt ← π_R.A, R.B, NULL AS C(NonMatched)

// Step 4: Union to get final result
Result ← NJ ∪ NullExt
